# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dns-filtering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] An **Internet filter** is a type of Internet censorship that restricts or controls the content an Internet user is capable to access, especially when utilized to restrict material delivered over the Internet via the Web, Email, or other means.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The motive is often to prevent access to content which the computer's owner(s) or other authorities may consider objectionable.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] When imposed without the consent of the user, content control can be characterised as a form of internet censorship.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Some filter software includes time control functions that empowers parents to set the amount of time that child may spend accessing the Internet or playing games or other computer activities.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The term "content control" is used on occasion by CNN, *Playboy* magazine, the *San Francisco Chronicle*, and *The New York Times*.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] However, several other terms, including "content filtering software", "web content filter", "filtering proxy servers", "secure web gateways", "censorware", "content security and control", "web filtering software", "content-censoring software", and "content-blocking software", are often used.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] "Nannyware" has also been used in both product marketing and by the media.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Industry research company Gartner uses **"secure web gateway"** (SWG) to describe the market segment.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Some products log all sites that a user accesses and rates them based on content type for reporting to an "accountability partner" of the person's choosing, and the term accountability software is used.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Internet filters, parental control software, and/or accountability software may also be combined into one product.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Those critical of such software, however, use the term "censorware" freely: consider the Censorware Project, for example.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Filters can be implemented in many different ways: by software on a personal computer, via network infrastructure such as proxy servers, DNS servers, or firewalls that provide Internet access.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] No solution provides complete coverage, so most companies deploy a mix of technologies to achieve the proper content control in line with their policies.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] E-mail filters act on information contained in the mail body, in the mail headers such as sender and subject, and e-mail attachments to classify, accept, or reject messages.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] , a type of statistical filter, are commonly used.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Both client and server based filters are available.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] This type of filter is installed as software on each computer where filtering is required.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] This filter can typically be managed, disabled or uninstalled by anyone who has administrator-level privileges on the system.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Content-limited (or filtered) ISPs are Internet service providers that offer access to only a set portion of Internet content on an opt-in or a mandatory basis.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Anyone who subscribes to this type of service is subject to restrictions.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] functionality to filter outbound as well as inbound information.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] All users are subject to the access policy defined by the institution.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The filtering can be customized, so a school district's high school library can have a different filtering profile than the district's junior high school library.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] This type of filtering is implemented at the DNS layer and attempts to prevent lookups for domains that do not fit within a set of policies (either parental control or company rules).
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] offer filtering options as part of their services.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] can be also be used for this purpose, though client-side only.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] offer users the option of turning on a safety filter.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] When this safety filter is activated, it filters out the inappropriate links from all of the search results.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] If users know the actual URL of a website that features explicit or adult content, they have the ability to access that content without using a search engine.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Some providers offer child-oriented versions of their engines that permit only child friendly websites.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Some offer security software which includes parental controls.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] operating system also includes content-control software.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The Internet does not intrinsically provide content blocking, and therefore there is much content on the Internet that is considered unsuitable for children, given that much content is given certifications as suitable for adults only, e.g.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Internet service providers (ISPs) that block material containing pornography, or controversial religious, political, or news-related content en route are often utilized by parents who do not permit their children to access content not conforming to their personal beliefs.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Content filtering software can, however, also be used to block malware and other content that is or contains hostile, intrusive, or annoying material including adware, spam, computer viruses, worms, trojan horses, and spyware.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Most content control software is marketed to organizations or parents.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] It is, however, also marketed on occasion to facilitate self-censorship, for example by people struggling with addictions to online pornography, gambling, chat rooms, etc.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Self-censorship software may also be utilised by some in order to avoid viewing content they consider immoral, inappropriate, or simply distracting.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] A number of accountability software products are marketed as *self-censorship* or *accountability software*.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] These are often promoted by religious media and at religious gatherings.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Content filtering technology exists in two major forms: application gateway or packet inspection.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] For HTTP access the application gateway is called a web-proxy or just a proxy.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Such web-proxies can inspect both the initial request and the returned web page using arbitrarily complex rules and will not return any part of the page to the requester until a decision is made.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] In addition they can make substitutions in whole or for any part of the returned result.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Packet inspection filters do not initially interfere with the connection to the server but inspect the data in the connection as it goes past, at some point the filter may decide that the connection is to be filtered and it will then disconnect it by injecting a TCP-Reset or similar faked packet.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The two techniques can be used together with the packet filter monitoring a link until it sees an HTTP connection starting to an IP address that has content that needs filtering.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The packet filter then redirects the connection to the web-proxy which can perform detailed filtering on the website without having to pass through all unfiltered connections.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] This combination is quite popular because it can significantly reduce the cost of the system.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] There are constraints to IP level packet-filtering, as it may result in rendering all web content associated with a particular IP address inaccessible.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] This may result in the unintentional blocking of legitimate sites that share the same IP address or domain.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] For instance, university websites commonly employ multiple domains under one IP address.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Moreover, IP level packet-filtering can be surpassed by using a distinct IP address for certain content while still being linked to the same domain or server.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Gateway-based content control software may be more difficult to bypass than desktop software as the user does not have physical access to the filtering device.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] However, many of the techniques in the Bypassing filters section still work.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Content labeling may be considered another form of content-control software.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] In 1994, the Internet Content Rating Association (ICRA) — now part of the Family Online Safety Institute — developed a content rating system for online content providers.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Using an online questionnaire a webmaster describes the nature of their web content.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] A small file is generated that contains a condensed, computer readable digest of this description that can then be used by content filtering software to block or allow that site.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] ICRA labels come in a variety of formats.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] These include the World Wide Web Consortium's Resource Description Framework (RDF) as well as Platform for Internet Content Selection (PICS) labels used by Microsoft's Internet Explorer Content Advisor.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] ICRA labels are an example of self-labeling.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Similarly, in 2006 the Association of Sites Advocating Child Protection (ASACP) initiated the Restricted to Adults self-labeling initiative.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] ASACP members were concerned that various forms of legislation being proposed in the United States were going to have the effect of forcing adult companies to label their content.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The RTA label, unlike ICRA labels, does not require a webmaster to fill out a questionnaire or sign up to use.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Both labels are recognized by a wide variety of content-control software.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The Voluntary Content Rating (VCR) system was devised by Solid Oak Software for their CYBERsitter filtering software, as an alternative to the PICS system, which some critics deemed too complex.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] It employs HTML metadata tags embedded within web page documents to specify the type of content contained in the document.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Only two levels are specified, *mature* and *adult*, making the specification extremely simple.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The Australian Internet Safety Advisory Body has information about "practical advice on Internet safety, parental control and filters for the protection of children, students and families" that also includes public libraries.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] NetAlert, the software made available free of charge by the Australian government, was allegedly cracked by a 16-year-old student, Tom Wood, less than a week after its release in August 2007.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Wood supposedly bypassed the $84 million filter in about half an hour to highlight problems with the government's approach to Internet content filtering.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The Australian Government has introduced legislation that requires ISPs to "restrict access to age restricted content (commercial MA15+ content and R18+ content) either hosted in Australia or provided from Australia" that was due to commence from 20 January 2008, known as Cleanfeed.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is a proposed mandatory ISP level content filtration system.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] It was proposed by the Beazley led Australian Labor Party opposition in a 2006 press release, with the intention of protecting children who were vulnerable due to claimed parental computer illiteracy.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] It was announced on 31 December 2007 as a policy to be implemented by the Rudd ALP government, and initial tests in Tasmania have produced a 2008 report.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is funded in the current budget, and is moving towards an Expression of Interest for live testing with ISPs in 2008.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Public opposition and criticism have emerged, led by the EFA and gaining irregular mainstream media attention, with a majority of Australians reportedly "strongly against" its implementation.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Criticisms include its expense, inaccuracy (it will be impossible to ensure only illegal sites are blocked) and the fact that it will be compulsory, which can be seen as an intrusion on free speech rights.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Another major criticism point has been that although the filter is claimed to stop certain materials, the underground rings dealing in such materials will not be affected.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The filter might also provide a false sense of security for parents, who might supervise children less while using the Internet, achieving the exact opposite effect.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is a responsibility of Senator Conroy's portfolio.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] In Denmark it is stated policy that it will "prevent inappropriate Internet sites from being accessed from children's libraries across Denmark".
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] "'It is important that every library in the country has the opportunity to protect children against pornographic material when they are using library computers.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Many libraries in the UK such as the British Library and local authority public libraries apply filters to Internet access.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] According to research conducted by the Radical Librarians Collective, at least 98% of public libraries apply filters; including categories such as "LGBT interest", "abortion" and "questionable".
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The use of Internet filters or content-control software varies widely in public libraries in the United States, since Internet use policies are established by the local library board.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Many libraries adopted Internet filters after Congress conditioned the receipt of universal service discounts on the use of Internet filters through the Children's Internet Protection Act (CIPA).
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Other libraries do not install content control software, believing that acceptable use policies and educational efforts address the issue of children accessing age-inappropriate content while preserving adult users' right to freely access information.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Some libraries use Internet filters on computers used by children only.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Many legal scholars believe that a number of legal cases, in particular *Reno v.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] American Civil Liberties Union*, established that the use of content-control software in libraries is a violation of the First Amendment.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The Children's Internet Protection Act [CIPA] and the June 2003 case *United States v.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The plurality decision left open a future "as-applied" Constitutional challenge, however.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] In November 2006, a lawsuit was filed against the North Central Regional Library District (NCRL) in Washington State for its policy of refusing to disable restrictions upon requests of adult patrons, but CIPA was not challenged in that matter.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The Court said: "It appears to us that NCRL's filtering policy is reasonable and accords with its mission and these policies and is viewpoint neutral.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] It appears that no article I, section 5 content-based violation exists in this case.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] NCRL's essential mission is to promote reading and lifelong learning.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] As NCRL maintains, it is reasonable to impose restrictions on Internet access in order to maintain an environment that is conducive to study and contemplative thought." The case returned to federal court.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] In March 2007, Virginia passed a law similar to CIPA that requires public libraries receiving state funds to use content-control software.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Like CIPA, the law requires libraries to disable filters for an adult library user when requested to do so by the user.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Utilizing a filter that is overly zealous at filtering content, or mislabels content not intended to be censored can result in over-blocking, or over-censoring.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Overblocking can filter out material that should be acceptable under the filtering policy in effect, for example health related information may unintentionally be filtered along with porn-related material because of the Scunthorpe problem.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Filter administrators may prefer to err on the side of caution by accepting over blocking to prevent any risk of access to sites that they determine to be undesirable.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Content-control software was mentioned as blocking access to Beaver College before its name change to Arcadia University.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Another example was the filtering of Horniman Museum.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] As well, over-blocking may encourage users to bypass the filter entirely.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Whenever new information is uploaded to the Internet, filters can under block, or under-censor, content if the parties responsible for maintaining the filters do not update them quickly and accurately, and a blacklisting rather than a whitelisting filtering policy is in place.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Many would not be satisfied with government filtering viewpoints on moral or political issues, agreeing that this could become support for propaganda.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Many would also find it unacceptable that an ISP, whether by law or by the ISP's own choice, should deploy such software without allowing the users to disable the filtering for their own connections.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] In the United States, the First Amendment to the United States Constitution has been cited in calls to criminalise forced internet censorship.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Many types of content-control software have been shown to block sites based on the religious and political leanings of the company owners.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Examples include blocking several religious sites (including the Web site of the Vatican), many political sites, and homosexuality-related sites.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] *X-Stop* was shown to block sites such as the Quaker web site, the National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law, The Heritage Foundation, and parts of The Ethical Spectacle.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] CYBERsitter blocks out sites like National Organization for Women.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Nancy Willard, an academic researcher and attorney, pointed out that many U.S. public schools and libraries use the same filtering software that many Christian organizations use.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] In 1998, a United States federal district court in Virginia ruled (Loudoun v.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Board of Trustees of the Loudoun County Library) that the imposition of mandatory filtering in a public library violates the First Amendment.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] In 1996 the US Congress passed the Communications Decency Act, banning indecency on the Internet.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Civil liberties groups challenged the law under the First Amendment, and in 1997 the Supreme Court ruled in their favor.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Part of the civil liberties argument, especially from groups like the Electronic Frontier Foundation, was that parents who wanted to block sites could use their own content-filtering software, making government involvement unnecessary.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] In the late 1990s, groups such as the Censorware Project began reverse-engineering the content-control software and decrypting the blacklists to determine what kind of sites the software blocked.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] This led to legal action alleging violation of the "Cyber Patrol" license agreement.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] They discovered that such tools routinely blocked unobjectionable sites while also failing to block intended targets.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Some content-control software companies responded by claiming that their filtering criteria were backed by intensive manual checking.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The companies' opponents argued, on the other hand, that performing the necessary checking would require resources greater than the companies possessed and that therefore their claims were not valid.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] The Motion Picture Association successfully obtained a UK ruling enforcing ISPs to use content-control software to prevent copyright infringement by their subscribers.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Content filtering in general can "be bypassed entirely by tech-savvy individuals." Blocking content on a device "[will not]…guarantee that users won't eventually be able to find a way around the filter." Content providers may change URLs or IP addresses to circumvent filtering.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Individuals with technical expertise may use a different method by employing multiple domains or URLs that direct to a shared IP address where restricted content is present.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] This strategy doesn't circumvent IP packet filtering, however can evade DNS poisoning and web proxies.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Additionally, perpetrators may use mirrored websites that avoid filters.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Some software may be bypassed successfully by using alternative protocols such as FTP or telnet or HTTPS, conducting searches in a different language, using a proxy server or a circumventor such as Psiphon.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Also cached web pages returned by Google or other searches could bypass some controls as well.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Web syndication services may provide alternate paths for content.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Some of the more poorly designed programs can be shut down by killing their processes: for example, in Microsoft Windows through the Windows Task Manager, or in Mac OS X using Force Quit or Activity Monitor.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Numerous workarounds and counters to workarounds from content-control software creators exist.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Google services are often blocked by filters, but these may most often be bypassed by using *https://* in place of *http://* since content filtering software is not able to interpret content under secure connections (in this case SSL).
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] An encrypted VPN can be used as means of bypassing content control software, especially if the content control software is installed on an Internet gateway or firewall.
[src:dns-filtering/content-control-software] Other ways to bypass a content control filter include translation sites and establishing a remote connection with an uncensored device.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] An alternative to DoH is the DNS over TLS (DoT) protocol, a similar standard for encrypting DNS queries, differing only in the methods used for encryption and delivery.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Based on privacy and security, whether either protocol is superior is a matter of debate, while others argue that the merits of either depend on the specific use case.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] DoH is a proposed standard, published as RFC 8484 (October 2018) by the IETF.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] It uses HTTPS, and supports the *wire format* DNS response data, as returned in existing UDP responses, in an HTTPS payload with the MIME type *application/dns-message*.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] The underlying HTTP layer can be any version of HTTP, though HTTP/2 is the *recommended* minimum.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] If HTTP/2 is used, the server may also use HTTP/2 server push to send values that it anticipates the client may find useful in advance.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Even though the IETF has published RFC 8484 as a proposed standard and companies are experimenting with it, the IETF has yet to determine how it should best be implemented.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] The IETF is evaluating a number of approaches for how best to deploy DoH and has established a working group, Adaptive DNS Discovery (ADD), to do this work and develop a consensus.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Since DoH cannot be used under some circumstances, like captive portals, web browsers like Firefox can be configured to fall back to insecure DNS.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] The de facto DoH URL is *https://host_name/dns-query*.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Oblivious DNS over HTTPS (ODoH) is an experimental standard, published as RFC 9230 (June 2022) by the IETF, proposing a protocol extension to ensure no single DoH server is aware of both the client's IP address and the content of their DNS queries and responses.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] This is an application of a security principle called decoupling or privacy partitioning.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] A different protocol with the same name (Oblivious DoH) was originally developed as Oblivious DNS (ODNS) by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH itself was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Apple and Cloudflare subsequently deployed the technology in the context of DoH, as Oblivious DoH (ODoH).
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] In ODoH and ODNS, all DNS requests and responses are routed via a proxy, hiding the client's address from the resolver.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Requests and responses are encrypted to hide their contents from the proxy, and only the resolver can decrypt the requests, and the client the responses.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Thus, the proxy knows the client address and resolver but not the request, and the resolver knows the proxy and request but not the client address, preventing the client address being linked to the query, unless both the proxy and resolver servers collude.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Another protocol, Oblivious HTTP, uses similar architectural principles for HTTP requests.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] DoH is used for recursive DNS resolution by DNS resolvers.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Resolvers (*DoH clients*) must have access to a DoH server hosting a query endpoint.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Apple's iOS 14 and macOS 11 released in late 2020 support both DoH and DoT protocols.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] In iOS, the protocols can be used via configuration profiles.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] In November 2019, Microsoft announced plans to implement support for encrypted DNS protocols in Microsoft Windows, beginning with DoH.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] In May 2020, Microsoft released Windows 10 Insider Preview Build 19628 that included initial support for DoH along with instructions on how to enable it via registry and command line interface.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Windows 10 Insider Preview Build 20185 added a graphical user interface for specifying a DoH resolver.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] DoH support is not included in Windows 10 21H2.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Android 11 onwards supports DNS over HTTP/3 (DoH3) if a July 2022 system update is installed.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] BIND 9, an open source DNS resolver from Internet Systems Consortium added native support for DoH in version 9.17.10.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] DNSdist, an open source DNS proxy/load balancer from PowerDNS, added native support for DoH in version 1.4.0 in April 2019.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Unbound, an open source DNS resolver created by NLnet Labs, has supported DoH since version 1.12.0, released in October 2020.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] It first implemented support for DNS encryption using the alternative DoT protocol much earlier, starting with version 1.4.14, released in December 2011.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Unbound runs on most operating systems, including distributions of Linux, BSD, MacOS, and Windows.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] DNS over HTTPS is available in Google Chrome 83 or later for Windows, Linux, and macOS, configurable via the settings page.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] When enabled, and the operating system is configured with a supported DNS server, Chrome will upgrade DNS queries to be encrypted.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] It is also possible to manually specify a preset or custom DoH server to use within the user interface.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] In September 2020, Google Chrome for Android began staged rollout of DNS over HTTPS.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Users can configure a custom resolver or disable DNS over HTTPS in settings.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Google Chrome has five DNS-over-HTTPS providers pre-configured, which are Google Public DNS, Cloudflare's 1.1.1.1, Quad9's 9.9.9.9, NextDNS, and CleanBrowsing.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Microsoft Edge supports DNS over HTTPS, configurable via the settings page.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] When enabled, and the operating system is configured with a supported DNS server, Edge will upgrade DNS queries to be encrypted.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] In 2018, Mozilla partnered with Cloudflare to deliver DoH for Firefox users that enable it (known as Trusted Recursive Resolver).
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] On February 25, 2020, Firefox started enabling DNS over HTTPS for all US-based users, relying on Cloudflare's resolver by default.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Opera supports DoH, configurable via the browser settings page.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] By default, DNS queries are sent to Cloudflare servers.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Brave implemented DNS over HTTPS (DoH) by default for its desktop browser in version 1.4, released in April 2020, as part of its broader privacy-focused features to encrypt DNS queries and prevent third-party eavesdropping or manipulation.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] DNS over HTTPS server implementations are already available free of charge by some public DNS providers.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] DoH can impede analysis and monitoring of DNS traffic for cybersecurity purposes; the 2019 DDoS worm Godlua used DoH to mask connections to its command-and-control server.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] In January 2021, NSA warned enterprises against using external DoH resolvers because they prevent DNS query filtering, inspection, and audit.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Instead, NSA recommends configuring enterprise-owned DoH resolvers and blocking all known external DoH resolvers.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] DoH has been used to bypass parental controls which operate at the (unencrypted) standard DNS level; However, there are DNS providers that offer filtering and parental controls along with support for DoH by operating DoH servers.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] In response to the criticism, the ISPA apologized and withdrew the nomination.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] Mozilla subsequently stated that DoH will not be used by default in the British market until further discussion with relevant stakeholders, but stated that it "would offer real security benefits to UK citizens".
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-https] In July 2020, iYouPort, the University of Maryland, and the Great Firewall Report, reported that the Great Firewall (GFW) by the Chinese government blocks TLS connections using the encrypted SNI extension in China.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] While DNS over TLS is applicable to any DNS transaction, it was first standardized for use between stub or forwarding resolvers and recursive resolvers, in RFC 7858 in May of 2016.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] Subsequent IETF efforts specify the use of DoT between recursive and authoritative servers ("Authoritative DNS over TLS" or "ADoT") and a related implementation between authoritative servers (Zone Transfer-over-TLS or "xfr-over-TLS").
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] BIND supports DoT connections as of version 9.17.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] Earlier versions offered DoT capability by proxying through stunnel.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] Unbound has supported DNS over TLS since 22 January 2023.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] Unwind has supported DoT since 29 January 2023.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] With Android Pie's support for DNS over TLS, some ad blockers now support using the encrypted protocol as a relatively easy way to access their services versus any of the various work-around methods typically used such as VPNs and proxy servers.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] Android clients running Android Pie or newer support DNS over TLS and will use it by default if the network infrastructure, for example the ISP, supports it.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] In April 2018, Google announced that Android Pie will include support for DNS over TLS, allowing users to set a DNS server phone-wide on both Wi-Fi and mobile connections, an option that was historically only possible on rooted devices or by using VPNService API.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] DNSDist, from PowerDNS, also announced support for DNS over TLS in version 1.3.0.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] Linux and Windows users can use DNS over TLS as a client through the NLnet Labs stubby daemon or Knot Resolver.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] Alternatively they may install getdns-utils to use DoT directly with the getdns_query tool.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] The unbound DNS resolver by NLnet Labs also supports DNS over TLS.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] Apple's iOS 14 introduced OS-level support for DNS over TLS (and DNS over HTTPS). iOS does not allow manual configuration of DoT servers, and requires the use of a third-party application to make configuration changes.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] systemd-resolved is a Linux-only implementation that can be configured to use DNS over TLS, by editing `/etc/systemd/resolved.conf` and enabling the setting `DNSOverTLS`.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] Most major Linux distributions have systemd installed by default.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] DNS over TLS was first implemented in a public recursive resolver by Quad9 in 2017.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] Other recursive resolver operators such as Google and Cloudflare followed suit in subsequent years, and now it is a broadly-supported feature generally available in most large recursive resolvers.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] DoT can impede analysis and monitoring of DNS traffic for cybersecurity purposes.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] DoT has been used to bypass parental controls which operate at the (unencrypted) standard DNS level; However, there are DNS providers that offer filtering and parental controls along with support for both DoT and DoH.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] In that scenario, DNS queries are checked against block lists once they are received by the provider rather than prior to leaving the user's router.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] As with any communication, encryption of DNS requests by itself does not protect privacy.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] It protects against third-party observers, but does not guarantee what the endpoints do with the (then decrypted) data.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] DoT clients do not necessarily directly query any authoritative name servers.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] The client may rely on the DoT server using traditional (port 53 or 853) queries to finally reach authoritative servers.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] Thus, DoT does not qualify as an end-to-end encrypted protocol, only hop-to-hop encrypted and only if DNS over TLS is used consistently.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] DNS over HTTPS (DoH) is a similar protocol standard for encrypting DNS queries, differing only in the methods used for encryption and delivery from DoT.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] On the basis of privacy and security, whether or not a superior protocol exists among the two is a matter of controversial debate, while others argue the merits of either depend on the specific use case.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-over-tls] DNSCrypt is another network protocol that authenticates and encrypts DNS traffic, although it was never proposed to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) with a Request for Comments (RFC).
[src:dns-filtering/dns-sinkhole] A **DNS sinkhole**, also known as a **sinkhole server**, **Internet sinkhole**, or **Blackhole DNS** is a Domain Name System (DNS) server that is configured to hand out non-routable addresses for a certain set of domain names.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-sinkhole] Computers that use the sinkhole fail to access the real site.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-sinkhole] The higher up the DNS resolution chain the sinkhole is, the more requests will fail, because of the greater number of lower nameservers that in turn serve a greater number of clients.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-sinkhole] Some of the larger botnets have been made unusable by top-level domain sinkholes that span the entire Internet.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-sinkhole] DNS Sinkholes are effective at detecting and blocking bots and other malicious traffic.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-sinkhole] By default, the local hosts file on a computer is checked before DNS servers, and can be used to block sites in the same way.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-sinkhole] Sinkholes can be used both constructively, to contain threats such as WannaCry and Avalanche, and destructively, for example disrupting DNS services in a DoS attack.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-sinkhole] DNS sinkholing can be used to protect users by intercepting DNS request attempting to connect to known malicious domains and instead returning an IP address of a sinkhole server defined by the DNS sinkhole administrator.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-sinkhole] One example of blocking malicious domains is to stop botnets, by interrupting the DNS names the botnet is programmed to use for coordination.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-sinkhole] Another use is to block ad serving sites, either using a host's file-based sinkhole or by locally running a DNS server (e.g., using a Pi-hole).
[src:dns-filtering/dns-sinkhole] Local DNS servers effectively block ads for all devices on the network.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] A Domain Name System server translates a human-readable domain name (such as `example.com`) into a numerical IP address that is used to route communications between nodes.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] Normally if the server does not know a requested translation it will ask another server, and the process continues recursively.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] To increase performance, a server will typically remember (cache) these translations for a certain amount of time.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] This means if it receives another request for the same translation, it can reply without needing to ask any other servers, until that cache expires.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] When a DNS server has received a false translation and caches it for performance optimization, it is considered *poisoned*, and it supplies the false data to clients.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] If a DNS server is poisoned, it may return an incorrect IP address, diverting traffic to another computer (often an attacker's).
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] Normally, a networked computer uses a DNS server provided by an Internet service provider (ISP) or the computer user's organization.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] DNS servers are used in an organization's network to improve resolution response performance by caching previously obtained query results.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] Poisoning attacks on a single DNS server can affect the users serviced directly by the compromised server or those serviced indirectly by its downstream server(s) if applicable.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] To perform a cache poisoning attack, the attacker exploits flaws in the DNS software.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] A server should correctly validate DNS responses to ensure that they are from an authoritative source (for example by using DNSSEC); otherwise the server might end up caching the incorrect entries locally and serve them to other users that make the same request.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] This attack can be used to redirect users from a website to another site of the attacker's choosing.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] For example, an attacker spoofs the IP address DNS entries for a target website on a given DNS server and replaces them with the IP address of a server under their control.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] The attacker then creates files on the server under their control with names matching those on the target server.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] These files usually contain malicious content, such as computer worms or viruses.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] A user whose computer has referenced the poisoned DNS server gets tricked into accepting content coming from a non-authentic server and unknowingly downloads the malicious content.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] This technique can also be used for phishing attacks, where a fake version of a genuine website is created to gather personal details such as bank and credit/debit card details.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] The vulnerability of systems to DNS cache poisoning goes beyond its immediate effects as it can open users up to further risks such as phishing, malware injections, denial of service, and website hijacking due to system vulnerabilities.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] Various methods, ranging from the use of social engineering tactics to the exploitation of weaknesses present in the DNS server software, can lead to these attacks.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] In the following variants, the entries for the server ns.target.example would be poisoned and redirected to the attacker's name server at IP address *w.x.y.z*.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] These attacks assume that the name server for target.example is ns.target.example.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] To accomplish the attacks, the attacker must force the target DNS server to make a request for a domain controlled by one of the attacker's nameservers.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] The first variant of DNS cache poisoning involves redirecting the name server of the attacker's domain to the name server of the target domain, then assigning that name server an IP address specified by the attacker.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] DNS server's request: what are the address records for subdomain.attacker.example?
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] A vulnerable server would cache the additional A-record (IP address) for ns.target.example, allowing the attacker to resolve queries to the entire target.example domain.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] The second variant of DNS cache poisoning involves redirecting the nameserver of another domain unrelated to the original request to an IP address specified by the attacker.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] A vulnerable server would cache the unrelated authority information for target.example's NS-record (nameserver entry), allowing the attacker to resolve queries to the entire target.example domain.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] Many cache poisoning attacks against DNS servers can be prevented by being less trusting of the information passed to them by other DNS servers, and ignoring any DNS records passed back that are not directly relevant to the query.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] For example, versions of BIND 9.5.0-P1 and above perform these checks.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] Source port randomization for DNS requests, combined with the use of cryptographically secure random numbers for selecting both the source port and the 16-bit cryptographic nonce, can greatly reduce the probability of successful DNS race attacks.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] However, when routers, firewalls, proxies, and other gateway devices perform network address translation (NAT), or more specifically, port address translation (PAT), they may rewrite source ports in order to track connection state.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] When modifying source ports, PAT devices may remove source port randomness implemented by nameservers and stub resolvers.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] Secure DNS (DNSSEC) uses cryptographic digital signatures signed with a trusted public key certificate to determine the authenticity of data.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] DNSSEC can counter cache poisoning attacks.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] In 2010 DNSSEC was implemented in the Internet root zone servers, but needs to be deployed on all top level domain servers as well.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] The DNSSEC readiness of these is shown in the list of Internet top-level domains.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] As of 2020, all of the original TLDs support DNSSEC, as do country code TLDs of most large countries, but many country-code TLDs still do not.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] Many second-level domains also do not support DNSSEC.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] This kind of attack can be mitigated at the transport layer or application layer by performing end-to-end validation once a connection is established.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] A common example of this is the use of Transport Layer Security and digital signatures.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] For example, by using HTTPS (the secure version of HTTP), users may check whether the server's digital certificate is valid and belongs to a website's expected owner.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] Similarly, the secure shell remote login program checks digital certificates at endpoints (if known) before proceeding with the session.
[src:dns-filtering/dns-spoofing] For applications that download updates automatically, the application can embed a copy of the signing certificate locally and validate the signature stored in the software update against the embedded certificate.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The **Domain Name System** (**DNS**) is a hierarchical and distributed name service that provides a naming system for computers, services, and other resources on the Internet or other Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] It associates various information with *domain names* (identification strings) assigned to each of the associated entities.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Most prominently, it translates readily memorized domain names to the numerical IP addresses needed for locating and identifying computer services and devices with the underlying network protocols.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System has been an essential component of the functionality of the Internet since 1985.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System delegates the responsibility of assigning domain names and mapping those names to Internet resources by designating authoritative name servers for each domain.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Network administrators may delegate authority over subdomains of their allocated name space to other name servers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This mechanism provides distributed and fault-tolerant service and was designed to avoid a single large central database.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In addition, the DNS specifies the technical functionality of the database service that is at its core.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] It defines the DNS protocol, a detailed specification of the data structures and data communication exchanges used in the DNS, as part of the Internet protocol suite.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The Internet maintains two principal namespaces, the domain name hierarchy and the IP address spaces.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System maintains the domain name hierarchy and provides translation services between it and the address spaces.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Internet name servers and a communication protocol implement the Domain Name System.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A DNS name server is a server that stores the DNS records for a domain; a DNS name server responds with answers to queries against its database.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The most common types of records stored in the DNS database are for start of authority (SOA), IP addresses (A and AAAA), SMTP mail exchangers (MX), name servers (NS), pointers for reverse DNS lookups (PTR), and domain name aliases (CNAME).
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Although not intended to be a general-purpose database, DNS has been expanded over time to store records for other types of data for either automatic lookups, such as DNSSEC records, or for human queries such as *responsible person* (RP) records.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] As a general-purpose database, the DNS has also been used in combating unsolicited email (spam) by storing blocklists.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The DNS database is conventionally stored in a structured text file, the zone file, but other database systems are common.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System originally used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) as transport over IP.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Reliability, security, and privacy concerns spawned the use of the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) as well as numerous other protocol developments.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] An often-used analogy to explain the DNS is that it serves as the phone book for the Internet by translating human-friendly computer hostnames into IP addresses.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The DNS can be quickly and transparently updated, allowing a service's location on the network to change without affecting the end users, who continue to use the same hostname.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Users take advantage of this when they use meaningful Uniform Resource Locators (URLs) and e-mail addresses without having to know how the computer actually locates the services.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] An important and ubiquitous function of the DNS is its central role in distributed Internet services such as cloud services and content delivery networks.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] When a user accesses a distributed Internet service using a URL, the domain name of the URL is translated to the IP address of a server that is proximal to the user.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The key functionality of the DNS exploited here is that different users can *simultaneously* receive different translations for the *same* domain name, a key point of divergence from a traditional phone-book view of the DNS.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This process of using the DNS to assign proximal servers to users is key to providing faster and more reliable responses on the Internet and is widely used by most major Internet services.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The DNS reflects the structure of administrative responsibility on the Internet.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Each subdomain is a zone of administrative autonomy delegated to a manager.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For zones operated by a registry, administrative information is often complemented by the registry's RDAP and WHOIS services.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] That data can be used to gain insight on, and track responsibility for, a given host on the Internet.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Using a simpler, more memorable name in place of a host's numerical address dates back to the ARPANET era.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) maintained a text file named HOSTS.TXT that mapped host names to the numerical addresses of computers on the ARPANET.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Elizabeth Feinler developed and maintained the first ARPANET directory.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Maintenance of numerical addresses, called the Assigned Numbers List, was handled by Jon Postel at the University of Southern California's Information Sciences Institute (ISI), whose team worked closely with SRI.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Computers, including their hostnames and addresses, were added to the primary file by contacting the SRI Network Information Center (NIC), directed by Feinler, via telephone during business hours.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Later, Feinler set up a WHOIS directory on a server in the NIC for retrieval of information about resources, contacts, and entities.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] She and her team developed the concept of domains.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Feinler suggested that domains should be based on the location of the physical address of the computer.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Computers at educational institutions would have the domain *edu*, for example.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] She and her team managed the Host Naming Registry from 1972 to 1989.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] By the early 1980s, maintaining a single, centralized host table had become slow and unwieldy and the emerging network required an automated naming system to address technical and personnel issues.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Postel directed the task of forging a compromise between five competing proposals of solutions to Paul Mockapetris.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Mockapetris instead created the Domain Name System in 1983 while at the University of Southern California.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The Internet Engineering Task Force published the original specifications in RFC 882 and RFC 883 in November 1983.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] These were updated in RFC 973 in January 1986.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In 1984, four UC Berkeley students, Douglas Terry, Mark Painter, David Riggle, and Songnian Zhou, wrote the first Unix name server implementation for the Berkeley Internet Name Domain, commonly referred to as BIND.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In 1985, Kevin Dunlap of DEC substantially revised the DNS implementation.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Mike Karels, Phil Almquist, and Paul Vixie then took over BIND maintenance.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Internet Systems Consortium was founded in 1994 by Rick Adams, Paul Vixie, and Carl Malamud, expressly to provide a home for BIND development and maintenance.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] BIND versions from 4.9.3 onward were developed and maintained by ISC, with support provided by ISC's sponsors.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] As co-architects/programmers, Bob Halley and Paul Vixie released the first production-ready version of BIND version 8 in May 1997.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Since 2000, over 43 different core developers have worked on BIND.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In November 1987, RFC 1034 and RFC 1035 superseded the 1983 DNS specifications.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Several additional Request for Comments have proposed extensions to the core DNS protocols.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The domain name space consists of a tree data structure.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Each node or leaf in the tree has a *label* and zero or more *resource records* (RR), which hold information associated with the domain name.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The domain name itself consists of the label, concatenated with the name of its parent node on the right, separated by a dot.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The tree sub-divides into *zones* beginning at the root zone.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A DNS zone may consist of as many domains and subdomains as the zone manager chooses.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNS can also be partitioned according to *class* where the separate classes can be thought of as an array of parallel namespace trees.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Administrative responsibility for any zone may be divided by creating additional zones.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Authority over the new zone is said to be *delegated* to a designated name server.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The parent zone ceases to be authoritative for the new zone.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The definitive descriptions of the rules for forming domain names appear in RFC 1035, RFC 1123, RFC 2181, and RFC 5892.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A domain name consists of one or more parts, technically called *labels*, that are conventionally concatenated, and delimited by dots, such as example.com.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The right-most label conveys the top-level domain; for example, the domain name www.example.com belongs to the top-level domain *com*.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The hierarchy of domains descends from right to left; each label to the left specifies a subdivision, or subdomain of the domain to the right.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For example, the label *example* specifies a subdomain of the *com* domain, and *www* is a subdomain of example.com.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This tree of subdivisions may have up to 127 levels.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A label may contain zero to 63 characters, because the length is only allowed to take 6 bits.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The null label of length zero is reserved for the root zone.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The full domain name may not exceed the length of 253 characters in its textual representation (or 254 with the trailing dot).
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In the internal binary representation of the DNS this maximum length of 253 requires 255 octets of storage, as it also stores the length of the first of many labels and adds last null byte.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] 255 length is only achieved with at least 6 labels (counting the last null label).
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Although no technical limitation exists to prevent domain name labels from using any character that is representable by an octet, hostnames use a preferred format and character set.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The characters allowed in labels are a subset of the ASCII character set, consisting of characters *a* through *z*, *A* through *Z*, digits *0* through *9*, and hyphen.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This rule is known as the *LDH rule* (letters, digits, hyphen).
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Domain names are interpreted in a case-independent manner.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Labels may not start or end with a hyphen.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] An additional rule requires that top-level domain names should not be all-numeric.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The limited set of ASCII characters permitted in the DNS prevented the representation of names and words of many languages in their native alphabets or scripts.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] To make this possible, ICANN approved the Internationalizing Domain Names in Applications (IDNA) system, by which user applications, such as web browsers, map Unicode strings into the valid DNS character set using Punycode.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In 2009, ICANN approved the installation of internationalized domain name country code top-level domains (*ccTLD*s).
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In addition, many registries of the existing top-level domain names (*TLD*s) have adopted the IDNA system, guided by RFC 5890, RFC 5891, RFC 5892, RFC 5893.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System is maintained by a distributed database system, which uses the client–server model.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The nodes of this database are the name servers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Each domain has at least one authoritative DNS server that publishes information about that domain and the name servers of any domains subordinate to it.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The top of the hierarchy is served by the root name servers, the servers to query when looking up (*resolving*) a TLD.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] An authoritative name server can either be a *primary* server or a *secondary* server.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Historically the terms *master/slave* and *primary/secondary* were sometimes used interchangeably but the current practice is to use the latter form.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A primary server is a server that stores the original copies of all zone records.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A secondary server uses a special automatic updating mechanism in the DNS protocol in communication with its primary to maintain an identical copy of the primary records.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Every DNS zone must be assigned a set of authoritative name servers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This set of servers is stored in the parent domain zone with name server (NS) records.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] An authoritative server indicates its status of supplying definitive answers, deemed *authoritative*, by setting a protocol flag, called the "*Authoritative Answer*" (*AA*) bit in its responses.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] When a name server is designated as the authoritative server for a domain name for which it does not have authoritative data, it presents a type of error called a "lame delegation" or "lame response".
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Domain name resolvers determine the domain name servers responsible for the domain name in question by a sequence of queries starting with the right-most (top-level) domain label.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For proper operation of its domain name resolver, a network host is configured with an initial cache (*hints*) of the known addresses of the root name servers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The hints are updated periodically by an administrator by retrieving a dataset from a reliable source.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Assuming the resolver has no cached records to accelerate the process, the resolution process starts with a query to one of the root servers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In typical operation, the root servers do not answer directly, but respond with a referral to more authoritative servers, e.g., a query for "www.wikipedia.org" is referred to the *org* servers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The resolver now queries the servers referred to, and iteratively repeats this process until it receives an authoritative answer.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The diagram illustrates this process for the host that is named by the fully qualified domain name "www.wikipedia.org".
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This mechanism would place a large traffic burden on the root servers, if every resolution on the Internet required starting at the root.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In practice caching is used in DNS servers to off-load the root servers, and as a result, root name servers actually are involved in only a relatively small fraction of all requests.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In theory, authoritative name servers are sufficient for the operation of the Internet.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] However, with only authoritative name servers operating, every DNS query must start with recursive queries at the root zone of the Domain Name System and each user system would have to implement resolver software capable of recursive operation.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Typically, such caching DNS servers also implement the recursive algorithm necessary to resolve a given name starting with the DNS root through to the authoritative name servers of the queried domain.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] With this function implemented in the name server, user applications gain efficiency in design and operation.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The combination of DNS caching and recursive functions in a name server is not mandatory; the functions can be implemented independently in servers for special purposes.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Internet service providers (ISP) typically provide recursive and caching name servers for their customers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In addition, many home networking routers implement DNS caches and recursion to improve efficiency in the local network.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The client side of the DNS is called a DNS resolver.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A resolver is responsible for initiating and sequencing the queries that ultimately lead to a full resolution (translation) of the resource sought, e.g., translation of a domain name into an IP address.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers are classified by a variety of query methods, such as *recursive*, *non-recursive*, and *iterative*.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A resolution process may use a combination of these methods.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In a *non-recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a DNS server that provides a record either for which the server is authoritative, or it provides a partial result without querying other servers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In case of a caching DNS resolver, the non-recursive query of its local DNS cache delivers a result and reduces the load on upstream DNS servers by caching DNS resource records for a period of time after an initial response from upstream DNS servers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In a *recursive query*, a DNS resolver queries a single DNS server, which may in turn query other DNS servers on behalf of the requester.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For example, a simple stub resolver running on a home router typically makes a recursive query to the DNS server run by the user's ISP.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A recursive query is one for which the DNS server answers the query completely by querying other name servers as needed.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In typical operation, a client issues a recursive query to a caching recursive DNS server, which subsequently issues non-recursive queries to determine the answer and send a single answer back to the client.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The resolver, or another DNS server acting recursively on behalf of the resolver, negotiates use of recursive service using bits in the query headers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNS servers are not required to support recursive queries.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The *iterative query* procedure is a process in which a DNS resolver queries a chain of one or more DNS servers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Each server refers the client to the next server in the chain, until the current server can fully resolve the request.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For example, a possible resolution of www.example.com would query a global root server, then a "com" server, and finally an "example.com" server.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Name servers in delegations are identified by name, rather than by IP address.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This means that a resolving name server must issue another DNS request to discover the IP address of the server to which it has been referred.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] If the name given in the delegation is a subdomain of the domain for which the delegation is being provided, there is a circular dependency.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In this case, the name server providing the delegation must also provide one or more IP addresses for the authoritative name server mentioned in the delegation.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The delegating name server provides this glue in the form of records in the *additional section* of the DNS response, and provides the delegation in the *authority section* of the response.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A glue record is a combination of the name server and IP address.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For example, if the authoritative name server for example.org is ns1.example.org, a computer trying to resolve www.example.org first resolves ns1.example.org.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] As ns1 is contained in example.org, this requires resolving example.org first, which presents a circular dependency.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] To break the dependency, the name server for the top level domain org includes glue along with the delegation for example.org.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The glue records are address records that provide IP addresses for ns1.example.org.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The resolver uses one or more of these IP addresses to query one of the domain's authoritative servers, which allows it to complete the DNS query.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A common approach to reduce the query load on DNS servers is to cache the results of name resolution locally or on intermediary resolver hosts.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Each DNS query result comes with a time to live (TTL), which indicates how long the information remains valid before it needs to be discarded or refreshed.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This TTL is determined by the administrator of the authoritative DNS server and can range from a few seconds to several days or even weeks.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] As a result of this distributed caching architecture, changes to DNS records do not propagate throughout the network immediately, but require all caches to expire and to be refreshed after the TTL.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] RFC 1912 conveys basic rules for determining appropriate TTL values.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Some resolvers may override TTL values, as the protocol supports caching for up to sixty-eight years or no caching at all.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Negative caching, i.e. the caching of the fact of non-existence of a record, is determined by name servers authoritative for a zone which must include the Start of Authority (SOA) record when reporting no data of the requested type exists.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The value of the *minimum* field of the SOA record and the TTL of the SOA itself is used to establish the TTL for the negative answer.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A reverse DNS lookup is a query of the DNS for domain names when the IP address is known.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Multiple domain names may be associated with an IP address.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The DNS stores IP addresses in the form of domain names as specially formatted names in pointer (PTR) records within the infrastructure top-level domain arpa.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For IPv6, the reverse lookup domain is ip6.arpa.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The IP address is represented as a name in reverse-ordered octet representation for IPv4, and reverse-ordered nibble representation for IPv6.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] When performing a reverse lookup, the DNS client converts the address into these formats before querying the name for a PTR record following the delegation chain as for any DNS query.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For example, assuming the IPv4 address 208.80.152.2 is assigned to Wikimedia, it is represented as a DNS name in reverse order: 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] When the DNS resolver gets a pointer (PTR) request, it begins by querying the root servers, which point to the servers of American Registry for Internet Numbers (ARIN) for the 208.in-addr.arpa zone.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] ARIN's servers delegate 152.80.208.in-addr.arpa to Wikimedia to which the resolver sends another query for 2.152.80.208.in-addr.arpa, which results in an authoritative response.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Users generally do not communicate directly with a DNS resolver.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Instead DNS resolution takes place transparently in applications such as web browsers, e-mail clients, and other Internet applications.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] When an application makes a request that requires a domain name lookup, such programs send a resolution request to the DNS resolver in the local operating system, which in turn handles the communications required.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The DNS resolver will almost invariably have a cache (see above) containing recent lookups.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] If the cache can provide the answer to the request, the resolver will return the value in the cache to the program that made the request.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] If the cache does not contain the answer, the resolver will send the request to one or more designated DNS servers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In any event, the name server thus queried will follow the process outlined above, until it either successfully finds a result or does not.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] It then returns its results to the DNS resolver; assuming it has found a result, the resolver duly caches that result for future use, and hands the result back to the software which initiated the request.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Some large ISPs have configured their DNS servers to violate rules, such as by disobeying TTLs, or by indicating that a domain name does not exist just because one of its name servers does not respond.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Some applications such as web browsers maintain an internal DNS cache to avoid repeated lookups via the network.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This practice can add extra difficulty when debugging DNS issues as it obscures the history of such data.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] These caches typically use very short caching times on the order of one minute.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer represents a notable exception: versions up to IE 3.x cache DNS records for 24 hours by default.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Internet Explorer 4.x and later versions (up to IE 8) decrease the default timeout value to half an hour, which may be changed by modifying the default configuration.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] When Google Chrome detects issues with the DNS server it displays a specific error message.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System includes several other functions and features.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Hostnames and IP addresses are not required to match in a one-to-one relationship.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Multiple hostnames may correspond to a single IP address, which is useful in virtual hosting, in which many web sites are served from a single host.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Alternatively, a single hostname may resolve to many IP addresses to facilitate fault tolerance and load distribution to multiple server instances across an enterprise or the global Internet.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNS serves other purposes in addition to translating names to IP addresses.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For instance, mail transfer agents use DNS to find the best mail server to deliver e-mail: An MX record provides a mapping between a domain and a mail exchanger; this can provide an additional layer of fault tolerance and load distribution.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The DNS is used for efficient storage and distribution of IP addresses of block-listed email hosts.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A common method is to place the IP address of the subject host into the sub-domain of a higher level domain name, and to resolve that name to a record that indicates a positive or a negative indication.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] E-mail servers can query blocklist.example to find out if a specific host connecting to them is in the block list.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Many such block lists, either subscription-based or free of cost, are available for use by email administrators and anti-spam software.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] To provide resilience in the event of computer or network failure, multiple DNS servers are usually provided for coverage of each domain.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] At the top level of global DNS, thirteen groups of root name servers exist, with additional "copies" of them distributed worldwide via anycast addressing.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS (DDNS) updates a DNS server with a client IP address on-the-fly, for example, when moving between ISPs or mobile hot spots, or when the IP address changes administratively.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The DNS protocol uses two types of DNS messages, queries and responses; both have the same format.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Each message consists of a header and four sections: question, answer, authority, and an additional space.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A header field (*flags*) controls the content of these four sections.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The header section consists of the following fields: *Identification*, *Flags*, *Number of questions*, *Number of answers*, *Number of authority resource records* (RRs), and *Number of additional RRs*.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Each field is 16 bits long, and appears in the order given.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The identification field is used to match responses with queries.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] After the flags word, the header ends with four 16-bit integers which contain the number of records in each of the sections that follow, in the same order.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Indicates if the message is a query (0) or a reply (1).
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The type can be QUERY (standard query, 0), IQUERY (inverse query, 1), or STATUS (server status request, 2).
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Authoritative Answer, in a response, indicates if the DNS server is authoritative for the queried hostname.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] TrunCation, indicates that this message was truncated due to excessive length.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Recursion Desired, indicates if the client means a recursive query.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Recursion Available, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server supports recursion.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Authentic Data, in a response, indicates if the replying DNS server verified the data.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Checking Disabled, in a query, indicates that non-verified data is acceptable in a response.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Response code, can be NOERROR (0), FORMERR (1, Format error), SERVFAIL (2), NXDOMAIN (3, Nonexistent domain), etc.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The question section has a simpler format than the resource record format used in the other sections.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The domain name is broken into discrete labels which are concatenated; each label is prefixed by the length of that label.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The Domain Name System specifies a database of information elements for network resources.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The types of information elements are categorized and organized with a list of DNS record types, the resource records (RRs).
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Each record has a type (name and number), an expiration time (time to live), a class, and type-specific data.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Resource records of the same type are described as a *resource record set* (RRset), having no special ordering.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNS resolvers return the entire set upon query, but servers may implement round-robin ordering to achieve load balancing.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In contrast, the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) work on the complete set of resource record in canonical order.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The *CLASS* of a record is set to IN (for *Internet*) for common DNS records involving Internet hostnames, servers, or IP addresses.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In addition, the classes Chaos (CH) and Hesiod (HS) exist.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Each class is an independent name space with potentially different delegations of DNS zones.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In addition to resource records defined in a zone file, the domain name system also defines several request types that are used only in communication with other DNS nodes (*on the wire*), such as when performing zone transfers (AXFR/IXFR) or for EDNS (OPT).
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The domain name system supports wildcard DNS records which specify names that start with the *asterisk label*, `*`, e.g., `*.example`.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNS records belonging to wildcard domain names specify rules for generating resource records within a single DNS zone by substituting whole labels with matching components of the query name, including any specified descendants.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For example, in the following configuration, the DNS zone *x.example* specifies that all subdomains, including subdomains of subdomains, of *x.example* use the mail exchanger (MX) *a.x.example*.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The AAAA record for *a.x.example* is needed to specify the mail exchanger IP address.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] As this has the result of excluding this domain name and its subdomains from the wildcard matches, an additional MX record for the subdomain *a.x.example*, as well as a wildcarded MX record for all of its subdomains, must also be defined in the DNS zone.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The role of wildcard records was refined in RFC 4592, because the original definition in RFC 1034 was incomplete and resulted in misinterpretations by implementers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The original DNS protocol had limited provisions for extension with new features.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In 1999, Paul Vixie published in RFC 2671 (superseded by RFC 6891) an extension mechanism, called Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS) that introduced optional protocol elements without increasing overhead when not in use.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This was accomplished through the OPT pseudo-resource record that only exists in wire transmissions of the protocol, but not in any zone files.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Initial extensions were also suggested (EDNS0), such as increasing the DNS message size in UDP datagrams.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Dynamic DNS updates use the UPDATE DNS opcode to add or remove resource records dynamically from a zone database maintained on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This facility is useful to register network clients into the DNS when they boot or become otherwise available on the network.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] As a booting client may be assigned a different IP address each time from a DHCP server, it is not possible to provide static DNS assignments for such clients.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] From the time of its origin in 1983 the DNS has used the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) for transport over IP.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Its limitations have motivated numerous protocol developments for reliability, security, privacy, and other criteria, in the following decades.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] UDP reserves port number 53 for servers listening to queries.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Such a query consists of a clear-text request sent in a single UDP packet from the client, responded to with a clear-text reply sent in a single UDP packet from the server.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] When the length of the answer exceeds 512 bytes and both client and server support Extension Mechanisms for DNS (EDNS), larger UDP packets may be used.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Use of DNS over UDP is limited by, among other things, its lack of transport-layer encryption, authentication, reliable delivery, and message length.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In 1989, RFC 1123 specified optional Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) transport for DNS queries, replies and, particularly, zone transfers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Via fragmentation of long replies, TCP allows longer responses, reliable delivery, and re-use of long-lived connections between clients and servers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For larger responses, the server refers the client to TCP transport.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNS over TLS emerged as an IETF standard for encrypted DNS in 2016, utilizing Transport Layer Security (TLS) to protect the entire connection, rather than just the DNS payload.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] RFC 7858 specifies that opportunistic encryption and authenticated encryption may be supported, but did not make either server or client authentication mandatory.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNS over HTTPS was developed as a competing standard for DNS query transport in 2018, tunneling DNS query data over HTTPS, which transports HTTP over TLS.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DoH was promoted as a more web-friendly alternative to DNS since, like DNSCrypt, it uses TCP port 443, and thus looks similar to web traffic, though they are easily differentiable in practice without proper padding.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] RFC 9250, published in 2022 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over QUIC.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] It has "privacy properties similar to DNS over TLS (DoT) [...], and latency characteristics similar to classic DNS over UDP".
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This method is not the same as DNS over HTTP/3.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] RFC 9953, published in 2026 by the Internet Engineering Task Force, describes DNS over CoAP.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The "application use case of DoC is inspired by DNS over HTTPS (DoH) (RFC 8484).
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] However, DoC aims for deployment in the constrained Internet of Things (IoT), which usually conflicts with the requirements introduced by HTTPS." DoC outperforms other DNS resolution mechanisms in constrained scenarios.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Oblivious DNS (ODNS) was invented and implemented by researchers at Princeton University and the University of Chicago as an extension to unencrypted DNS, before DoH was standardized and widely deployed.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] ODoH combines ingress/egress separation (invented in ODNS) with DoH's HTTPS tunneling and TLS transport-layer encryption in a single protocol.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNS may be run over virtual private networks (VPNs) and tunneling protocols.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The privacy gains of Oblivious DNS can be garnered through the use of the preexisting Tor network of ingress and egress nodes, paired with the transport-layer encryption provided by TLS.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt uses either TCP port 443, the same port as HTTPS encrypted web traffic, or UDP port 443.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This introduced not only privacy regarding the content of the query, but also a significant measure of firewall-traversal capability.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Privacy of user/query pairs is created, since the ingress node does not know the content of the query, while the egress node does not know the identity of the client.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNSCrypt was first implemented in production by OpenDNS in December 2011.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] There are several free and open source software implementations that additionally integrate ODoH.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] It is available for a variety of operating systems, including Unix, Apple iOS, Linux, Android, and Windows.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Originally, security concerns were not major design considerations for DNS software or any software for deployment on the early Internet, as the network was not open for participation by the general public.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] However, the expansion of the Internet into the commercial sector in the 1990s changed the requirements for security measures to protect data integrity and user authentication.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Several vulnerability issues were discovered and exploited by malicious users.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] One such issue is DNS cache poisoning, in which data is distributed to caching resolvers under the pretense of being an authoritative origin server, thereby polluting the data store with potentially false information and long expiration times (time-to-live).
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Subsequently, legitimate application requests may be redirected to network hosts operated with malicious intent.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNS responses traditionally do not have a cryptographic signature, leading to many attack possibilities; the Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) modify DNS to add support for cryptographically signed responses.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNSCurve has been proposed as an alternative to DNSSEC.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Other extensions, such as TSIG, add support for cryptographic authentication between trusted peers and are commonly used to authorize zone transfer or dynamic update operations.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Techniques such as forward-confirmed reverse DNS can also be used to help validate DNS results.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNS can also "leak" from otherwise secure or private connections, if attention is not paid to their configuration, and at times DNS has been used to bypass firewalls by malicious persons, and exfiltrate data, since it is often seen as innocuous.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Some domain names may be used to achieve spoofing effects.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For example, paypal.com and paypa1.com are different names, yet users may be unable to distinguish them in a graphical user interface depending on the user's chosen typeface.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In many fonts the letter *l* and the numeral *1* look very similar or even identical.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This problem, known as the IDN homograph attack, is acute in systems that support internationalized domain names, as many character codes in ISO 10646 may appear identical on typical computer screens.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This vulnerability is occasionally exploited in phishing.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger is a type of cyber attack technique that uses the DNS to communicate and control malware remotely without relying on conventional protocols that might raise red flags.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The DNSMessenger attack is covert because DNS is primarily used for domain name resolution and is often not closely monitored by network security tools, making it an effective channel for attackers to exploit.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This technique involves the use of DNS TXT records to send commands to infected systems.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Once malware has been surreptitiously installed on a victim's machine, it reaches out to a controlled domain to retrieve commands encoded in DNS text records.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This form of malware communication is stealthy, as DNS requests are usually allowed through firewalls, and because DNS traffic is often seen as benign, these communications can bypass many network security defenses.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] DNSMessenger attacks can enable a wide array of malicious activities, from data exfiltration to the delivery of additional payloads, all while remaining under the radar of traditional network security measures.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Understanding and defending against such methods are crucial for maintaining robust cybersecurity.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Originally designed as a public, hierarchical, distributed and heavily cached database, the DNS protocol has no confidentiality controls.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] User queries and nameserver responses are sent unencrypted, enabling network packet sniffing, DNS hijacking, DNS cache poisoning and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] This deficiency is commonly used by cybercriminals and network operators for marketing purposes, user authentication on captive portals and censorship.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] User privacy is further exposed by proposals for increasing the level of client IP information in DNS queries (RFC 7871) for the benefit of content delivery networks.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Solutions preventing DNS inspection by the local network operator have been criticized for thwarting corporate network security policies and Internet censorship.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Public DNS servers are also criticized for contributing to the centralization of the Internet by placing control over DNS resolution in the hands of the few large companies which can afford to run public resolvers.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The right to use a domain name is delegated by domain name registrars which are accredited by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN) or other organizations such as OpenNIC, that are charged with overseeing the name and number systems of the Internet.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In addition to ICANN, each top-level domain (TLD) is maintained and serviced technically by an administrative organization, operating a registry.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A *registry* is responsible for operating the database of names within its authoritative zone, although the term is most often used for TLDs.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] A *registrant* is a person or organization who asked for domain registration.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The registry receives registration information from each domain name *registrar*, which is authorized (accredited) to assign names in the corresponding zone and publishes the information using the WHOIS protocol.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] As of 2015, usage of RDAP is being considered.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] ICANN publishes the complete list of TLDs, TLD registries, and domain name registrars.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Registrant information associated with domain names is maintained in an online database accessible with the WHOIS service.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For most of the more than 290 country code top-level domains (ccTLDs), the domain registries maintain the WHOIS (Registrant, name servers, expiration dates, etc.) information.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For instance, DENIC, Germany NIC, holds the DE domain data.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] From about 2001, most generic top-level domain (gTLD) registries have adopted this so-called *thick* registry approach, i.e. keeping the WHOIS data in central registries instead of registrar databases.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] For top-level domains on COM and NET, a *thin* registry model is used.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The domain registry (GoDaddy, BigRock and PDR, VeriSign, etc.) holds basic WHOIS data (i.e., registrar and name servers, etc.).
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] On the other hand, organizations, i.e., registrants using ORG, are on the Public Interest Registry exclusively.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] Some domain name registries, often called *network information centers* (NIC), also function as registrars to end-users, in addition to providing access to the WHOIS datasets.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The top-level domain registries, such as for the domains COM, NET, and ORG use a registry-registrar model consisting of many domain name registrars.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] In this method of management, the registry only manages the domain name database and the relationship with the registrars.
[src:dns-filtering/domain-name-system] The *registrants* (users of a domain name) are customers of the registrar, in some cases through additional subcontracting of resellers.
